A better year for migrants?
DUBLIN – Two major lessons emerge from the Mediterranean migration crisis.
First, Europe and the international community apply a system cruelly ill-suited for the protection of the most vulnerable migrants.
Secondly, in the face of the ineffectiveness of this system, populist actors continue to exploit fears in order to gain political support, undermining liberal and tolerant societies whose construction has required some 70 years of relentless effort.
This is the reason why it is essential that a truly active approach be undertaken this year at the European and global levels.
In September next, United Nations Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon will convene an extraordinary summit to build a sound global system for protecting the most vulnerable migrants and refugees.
Let's hope that the states will be ready to commit in a concrete and lasting manner.
This necessary commitment was cruelly lacking throughout the year 2015.
In fact, the international community would have been able to limit the gravity of last year's crisis if it had provided even the most modest support to the frontline countries – Turkey, Lebanon, and Jordan – which together host no less than four million refugees.
With approximately €10 billion, these countries would have been more capable of housing, feeding, and providing education to refugees, thereby reducing the temptation of a flight to Europe.
This failure could cost Germany up to €21 billion each year in the years to come.
But the financial implications of the crisis are incommensurable with its human and political cost.
More than a million people risked their lives last year by crossing the Mediterranean, enduring an exhausting journey through the Balkans afterwards.
Nearly 4,000 migrants lost their lives there, many European countries meanwhile turning their backs on survivors by refusing them refuge.
Politicians with the most cynical views have ruthlessly exploited citizens' fear by promoting a detestable nationalist vision, which either ignores or distorts the migrant experience.
In the United States, for example, not a single one of the 780,000 refugees settled since September 11, 2001, has committed an act of terrorism.
At the same time, immigrants generally pay more taxes than they benefit from social benefits.
However, extreme parties are dangerously flirting with the seizure of political power in some European countries, and are currently gaining support within the very heart of former liberal bastions.
Anti-immigration parties are already in power in Hungary and Poland.
Their success, on the other hand, leads traditional parties to also promote a hostile immigration policy.
This situation has significantly undermined European cooperation.
The EU program aimed at dealing with the million refugees who arrived on its shores has only allowed for the "relocation" of 190.
Controls at the borders of six Schengen countries have been reinstated, at least temporarily.
In the eyes of the rest of the world, the EU appears today as chauvinistic and incompetent.
Of course, the resolution of this crisis does not only concern Europe; responsibility cannot be defined by simple geographical proximity.
Whatever the case, the EU is undoubtedly facing a threat to its own existence today, one it can only overcome by firmly demonstrating the international solidarity and leadership it is capable of.
That is why it is up to the member states to take the initiative by proposing solutions.
The most urgent priority is to establish safe and legal routes for refugees to reach Europe.
It is not a matter of asserting that every migrant in difficulty must be received.
It remains however to the EU to be more systematically generous in its determination of the number of refugees to host, and to employ ordered mechanisms aimed at facilitating their entry.
Such a system would protect migrants while preserving Europe (thanks to the possibility of fully examining the applications).
Beyond a move intended to dissuade asylum seekers from risking their lives crossing the Mediterranean, such an approach would allow for projecting an image of solidarity towards frontline countries, which continue to host the majority of refugees.
This approach would equally encourage the rest of the international community to contribute to the efforts.
This leads us to the second priority of the year 2016: building a sound global refugee and vulnerable migrant protection system.
This goal will above all require more countries to agree to host refugees.
In recent years, the United Nations agency for refugees has only managed to resettle less than 75,000 of the approximately 20 million refugees annually.
Several million of them end up in a prolonged migration situation, with an estimated average duration of 25 years, trapped in a kind of purgatory, uncertain about the day of a potential return to their country.
In 2016, it is necessary that developed countries agree to host a cumulative total of nearly one million refugees each year, either through their resettlement or by granting them humanitarian, student, professional, or other visas.
Canada having said it would alone welcome 50,000 Syrian refugees this year, it is clearly an achievable goal.
At the same time, the international community will need to support the integration of refugees in major host countries such as Turkey, Kenya, Lebanon, and Jordan.
In the current state of affairs, these countries are only receiving a fraction of the $3,000 to $5,000 annually needed for each refugee for housing, food, care, education, and vocational training during the first years of settlement.
And these numbers do not take into account the necessary cost of construction or upgrading of the infrastructure.
In Lebanon, for example, the water supply systems suffer from the pressure exerted by the massive arrival of refugees.
In exchange for funding, these host countries could commit to fully integrating refugees into their schools, labor market, and civil institutions.
However, effective migrant integration will only be possible if European countries and others shed their prejudices concerning migrants.
If these individuals are seen as a burden, or even a security threat, reactionary political forces will continue to gain ground, depriving new arrivals of opportunities and turning fear into a self-fulfilling prophecy.
In contrast, if welcoming countries are able to integrate migrants with enthusiasm, each will find benefit in it – including these countries (notably through income streams).
Last month in Paris, the international community proved that it was capable of subordinating its national interests to a broader global objective: fighting global climate change.
In 2016, it is necessary that a similar effort aims to build a better protection system for migrants.
It's a matter of life or death for nearly 20 million refugees, for several million other vulnerable migrants – as well as a profound test of the civic health of democratic societies around the world.
